[[Category:Evolutionary biology terminology]]

'''Channel spacing''', also known as '''[[Bandwidth_(signal_processing)#Overview|bandwidth]]''', is a term used in radio [[frequency]] planning. It describes the frequency difference between adjacent allocations in a frequency plan. Channels for [[mediumwave]] radio stations, for example are allocated in internationally agreed steps of 9 or 10 [[kHz]]: 10 kHz in ITU Region 2 (the Americas) and 9 kHz elsewhere in the world.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/62hRKETJE?url=http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/cfr_2006/octqtr/47cfr73.44.htm US 47CFR73.44 AM transmission system emission limitations]</ref>

